    "# Interview Prep: 01 - Core Fundamentals\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook covers the basic but often tricky parts of Python. Even if you are an experienced developer, these \"trap\" questions are common in initial technical screenings.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Lists vs. Tuples\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Interview Question**: \"When would you use a tuple instead of a list?\"\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **Key Talking Points**:\n",
    "- **Immutability**: Tuples cannot be changed. This makes them \"hashable\" and suitable as keys in a dictionary.\n",
    "- **Memory**: Tuples are more memory-efficient than lists because their size is fixed on creation.\n",
    "- **Semantics**: Use lists for collections of the same type of data. Use tuples for \"records\" or heterogenous data (e.g., `(latitude, longitude)`).\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Mutable Default Arguments\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Interview Question**: \"What is wrong with the following function definition?\"\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "def add_to_list(val, my_list=[]):\n",
    "    my_list.append(val)\n",
    "    return my_list\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "**The Problem**: In Python, default arguments are evaluated only **once** at function definition time, not every time the function is called. If you pass a mutable object (like a list), that same object is reused across all calls.\n",
    "\n",
    "**The Solution**: `def add_to_list(val, my_list=None):` and then check `if my_list is None: my_list = []` inside the function.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Identity (`is`) vs Equality (`==`)\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Interview Question**: \"Explain the difference between `is` and `==`.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "**Answer**:\n",
    "- `==`: Compares **Values**. (Are they the same size/content?)\n",
    "- `is`: Compares **Identity/Memory Address**. (Are they literally the same object in memory?)\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **Bonus Tip**: Python caches small integers (-5 to 256), so `256 is 256` is True, but `1000 is 1000` might be False depending on the interpreter environment.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Coding Challenge: Balanced Parentheses\n",
    "\n",
    "**Task**: Write a function that takes a string of parentheses and returns `True` if they are balanced and closed in the correct order.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def is_balanced(s):\n",
    "    stack = []\n",
    "    mapping = {\")\": \"(\", \"}\": \"{\", \"]\": \"[\"}\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for char in s:\n",
    "        if char in mapping:\n",
    "            top_element = stack.pop() if stack else '#'\n",
    "            if mapping[char] != top_element:\n",
    "                return False\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            stack.append(char)\n",
    "            \n",
    "    return not stack\n",
    "\n",
    "# Test cases\n",
    "print(f\"'({'{'}'}'}'': {is_balanced('({[]})')}\") # True\n",
    "print(f\"'([)]': {is_balanced('([)]')}\")     # False\n")
   ]
  }
